Exploring Red Wine Quality by Chun Zhu

About

In this exercise, I will explore the dataset of red wine quality. Id like to find out which chemical properties influence the quality of red wines. This tidy data set contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

Summary of the Dataset

Bivariate Plots Section

First Id like to investigate the correlation between any 2 variables in the data set. (note that I use log10(sulphates) in the analysis)

Bivariate Analysis

Some Observations: * Input pairs with strong positive correlation: + fixed.acidity and citric.acid + fixed.acidity and density + free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide

  • Input pairs with strong negative correlation:
  • fixed.acidity and pH
  • volatile.acidity and citric.acid
  • citric.acid and pH
  • density and alcohol

We need to be aware of strong correlation among input variables to avoid multicollinear effect in model builing.

Another interest topic is to find out the correlation between output variable quality and input variables.

Some findings:

  • quality is strongly correlated with alcohol (~0.476)
  • quality is moderately correlated with volatile.acidity (~-0.391), citric.acid (0.226) and sulphates (0.309).
  • Correlation is not that strong between quality and other input variables.

Multivariate Plots Section

Based on the bivariate analysis above, I am most interested in 4 variables - alcohol, volatile.acidity, citric.acid and sulphates, as these 4 variables have some correlations with wine quality.

Since quality is strongly correlated with alcohol, moderately correlated with volatile.acidity, while the correlation between alcohol and volatile.acidity is not big, Ill first check how alcohol and volatile.acidity affect quality.

It is difficult to find out the pattern due to the wide range of quality. So Ill catergorize quality into 3 classes: poor, average, good. Poor is for quality from 0 to 4; average is for quality from 5 to 6; good is for quality from 7 to 10.

##     bad average    good 
##      63    1319     217

Below is the scatter plot of red wine ratings on alcohol and volatile.acidity.

There seems to a relationship between alcohol percentage and wine quality. To examine the relationship better, Ill just plot bad and good red wine.

from the above graph, we can see that good wines are more likely with higher alcohol percentage and lower volatile.acidity.

Next lets examine how alcohol and citric.acid affect ratings.

Its clear that good wines are more likely with higher alcohol percentage and higher citric.acid. This conclusion is consistent with the correlation results.

Alcohol and sulphates plot:

Its clear that good wines are more likely with higher alcohol percentage and higher sulphates This conclusion is consistent with the correlation results.

volatile.acidity and citric.acid plot:

Its clear that good wines are more likely with lower volatile.acidity and higher citric.acid. This plot also show that volatile.acidity and citric.acid have a strong negative correlation. This conclusion is consistent with the correlation results.

volatile.acidity and sulphates plot:

Its clear that good wines are more likely with lower volatile.acidity and higher sulphates. This conclusion is consistent with the correlation results.

citric.acid and sulphates plot:

Its clear that good wines are more likely with higher citric.acid and higher sulphates. This conclusion is consistent with the correlation results.

Multivariate Analysis

From the above plots, we can conclude that higher alcohol, lower volatile.acidity, higher citric.acid and higher sulphates are more likely to result in better red wines.

Description One

The histogram of wine quality shows that the quality generally follows normal distribution. Most red wines are rated between 5 and 6.

Plot Two: Effect of Alcohol levels on Red Wine Quality

Description Two

These boxplots clearly demonstrate that wine qaulity is generally better with higher alcohol levels. At the meantime, alcohol alone does not produce a higher quality.

Plot Three:Features affect Red Wine Quality

Description Three

From the correlation study, we know that alcohol and volatile acidity have the highest correlation with quality. Plot 3 clearly supports this point. from the above graph, we can see that a combination of high alcohol levels and low volatile acidity produced better red wines.

Reflection

From this exploratory data analysis, I was able to identity several main features which affect red wine quality: alcohol, volatile acidity and sulphates. alcohol has positive relationship with the quality of red wine while Volatile Acidity has negative one. Further analysis can be done by building a model to predict red wine quality by the 2 features: alcohol and volatile acidity.
